# Pagefolk

Reading tracker built with Next.js App Router, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, Supabase (`@supabase/ssr`, RLS), React Query, and Vercel AI SDK (tool calling + streaming). Package manager: **pnpm**. All code, comments, and UI text in **English**.

## Folder structure

```
src/
  app/          # Routes, layouts, pages, route handlers, Server Actions
  components/   # UI components (Server by default; Client when needed)
  hooks/        # Custom React hooks (UI state, browser APIs, React Query, etc.)
  lib/          # Supabase clients, query client, shared utilities
  providers/    # Client providers (QueryProvider, etc.)
  types/        # Shared TypeScript types
```

- Put new code in the matching folder; do not invent parallel structures.
- Use `@/` path aliases for imports within `src/`.

## Next.js & React

- **App Router only** — no Pages Router (`pages/`, `getServerSideProps`, `getStaticProps`).
- **Server Components by default** — add `'use client'` only for interactivity, state, effects, or browser APIs.
- **React Query for all CRUD and client data fetching** — no ad-hoc `useEffect` + `fetch`. Put query/mutation hooks in `src/hooks/`.
- **`src/hooks/`** is for any reusable client hook — not only React Query (e.g. form state, media queries, keyboard shortcuts).
- **Vercel AI SDK** for the AI agent — streaming responses, tool calling; keep agent logic in `src/lib/` or route handlers.

## TypeScript

- Strict mode; no `any` without a brief inline justification.
- Prefer explicit types for props, API responses, and Supabase row shapes.
- Validate external input with Zod at boundaries.

## Supabase

- Use `@supabase/ssr` for server and browser clients.
- Assume **RLS is enabled** — never bypass with service-role keys in client code.
- Data access in `src/lib/`; expose to UI via React Query hooks in `src/hooks/`.

## Code quality

- Small, focused functions and components; meaningful names.
- Clear separation: server logic (`app/`, Server Actions), client UI (`components/`), client hooks (`hooks/`), utilities and data access (`lib/`).
- Tailwind for styling; follow `styles.mdc`.

## Git workflow

- **Conventional commits**: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:` (etc.).
- **Conventional branch prefixes**: `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `refactor/` — only create a branch when asked.
- **Pull requests** — only create when asked; never push or open PRs unprompted.
